Motor Trend: mpg regression

bdanalytics

Date: (Wed) Oct 22, 2014

Data: Motor Trend Car Road Tests “mtcars {datasets}”
Source: Henderson and Velleman (1981), Building multiple regression models interactively. Biometrics, 37, 391–411.
Time period: 1973–74 models

Synopsis:

Is an automatic or manual transmission better for MPG:

Manual transmission is better for miles per gallon versus automatic transmission.
Average mpg for automatic transmission is 17 vs. 23 for manual transmission.

Quantify the MPG difference between automatic and manual transmissions:

The univariate model yields mpg ~ 17.15 + 7.25 * manual while explaining only 33.8% of the mpg variation.

The proposed multivariate model yields mpg ~ 46.30 - 9.08 * wt for cars with manual transmission and mpg ~ 31.42 - 3.79 * wt for cars with automatic transmission. This model explains 81.5% of the mpg variation at a 99% confidence level. The most influential data point turned out to be Maserati Bora which would decrease the predicted mpg by 0.98 - did not know until now that Maseratis are that efficient.

The model for variation from mean wt did not pass the statistical significance tests. Additional features were not statistically significant and/or explain additional mpg variation. The proposed model contains minor negative correlation of residuals with predicted values.

Potential next steps include:

  1. Test other regression techniques (e.g. additive models in glm) to better quantify the relationship.
  2. Add Maserati labels to points in scatter plots to better understand it’s influence on the model
  3. ???

Is an automatic or manual transmission better for MPG:

Null Hypothesis (\(\sf{H_{0}}\)): mpg is not impacted by am_fctr.
The variance by am_fctr appears to be independent.

print(t.test(subset(cars_df, am_fctr == "automatic")$mpg, 
             subset(cars_df, am_fctr == "manual")$mpg, 
             var.equal=FALSE)$conf)
## [1] -11.28  -3.21
## attr(,"conf.level")
## [1] 0.95

We reject the null hypothesis i.e. we have evidence to conclude that am_fctr impacts mpg (95% confidence). Manual transmission is better for miles per gallon versus automatic transmission.

Quantify the MPG difference between automatic and manual transmissions:

Let’s try the univariate model to establish a benchmark against which we can evaluate more complex models, if necessary

mpg_fit <- lm(mpg ~ am_fctr, data=cars_df)
print(summary(mpg_fit))

This univariate model is statistically significant and explains 33.8% of the mpg variation.

Manual Transmission provides 7.24 additional miles per gallon compared to automatic transmission. This result is highly significant - 95% confidence interval is [ 3.64, 10.85].

Let’s inspect the residuals for any bias

build_fit_df <- function(fit) {
    df <- data.frame(mpg.predict=predict(fit, cars_df), 
                     mpg.residuals=fit$residuals,
                     mpg=cars_df$mpg, am_fctr=cars_df$am_fctr, id=cars_df$id)
    df <- cbind(df, cars_df[, feats_fctr[feats_fctr != "am_fctr"]])
    df <- cbind(df, cars_df[, feats_num[feats_num != "mpg"]])
}
mpg_fit_df <- build_fit_df(mpg_fit)

print(myplot_violin(mpg_fit_df, "mpg.residuals", "mpg.predict"))

build_fit_plot_df <- function(fit_df) {
    fit_plot_df <- melt(fit_df[, c("id", "mpg", "mpg.predict", "mpg.residuals", 
                                           feats_fctr, feats_num)], 
                            id.vars=c("id", "mpg", "mpg.predict", "mpg.residuals", 
                                      "am_fctr"))
    fit_plot_df <- orderBy(~ id + variable, fit_plot_df)
    #tail(fit_df)
    #tail(fit_plot_df, 10)
    #intersect(names(fit_plot_df), names(mpg_cor_df[, c("variable", "label")]))
    fit_plot_df <- merge(fit_plot_df, mpg_cor_df[, c("variable", "label")],
                                 all.x=TRUE)
    fit_plot_df <- orderBy(~ id + variable, fit_plot_df)
    return(fit_plot_df)
}

extract_fit_formula <- function(fit) {
    str <- strsplit(toString(summary(fit)$call$formula), ',')
    tmp_str <- str[[1]]
    str <- paste0(tmp_str[2], " ", tmp_str[1], tmp_str[3:length(tmp_str)])
}

build_fit_formula <- function(fit) {
    str <- strsplit(toString(summary(fit)$call$formula), ',')
    tmp_str <- str[[1]]
    regressors <- strsplit(tmp_str[3], split=' ')[[1]]
    regressors <- regressors[regressors != '+']
    coeff <- summary(fit)$coefficients
    coeff_str <- ""
    for (row in seq(1:nrow(coeff)))
    #for (row in seq(1:2))        
        coeff_str <- paste0(coeff_str, ifelse((row == 1), "", " + "), 
                            format(coeff[row, 1], digits=4), 
                            ifelse((row == 1), "", " * "), regressors[row])                            
    print(coeff_str)
    str <- paste0(tmp_str[2], " ", tmp_str[1], " ", coeff_str)
    return(str)
}
display_fit_frmla <- build_fit_formula(mpg_wt_i_fit)

The proposed model is mpg ~ 31.42 + 14.88 * am_fctr + -3.786 * wt + -5.298 * am_fctr:wt where am_fctr is 0 for manual transmission [1 for automatic], wt is weight (lb/1000) and am_fctr:wt is 0 for manual transmission [wt for automatic].
